commit.message:
Slight optimization of getCompressedData.

We don't need to build a list of decompressed chunks,
because we only care about finding the end of the compressed data.

Use streaming decompress to identify extent of compressed data. (#66)

This fixes a problem that arises for local files with bit 3
of the general purpose bit flag set. In this case, we don't
get information up front about the size of the compressed
data.  So how do we know where the compressed data ends?
Previously, we tried to determine this by looking for the
signature of the data descriptor. But the data descriptor doesn't
always HAVE a signature, and it is also possible for signatures to
occur accidentally in the compressed data itself (#65).

Here we follow a clue from an Info-ZIP note:
"In general, this feature can only be reliably used
together with compression methods that allow intrinsic
detection of the 'end-of-compressed-data' condition."

We use the streaming decompression interface from
zlib's Internal module.  This tells us, in effect, where
the compressed data ends.

A parameter has been added to getCompressedData for
the compressionMethod, since we only want to do streaming
decompression if the data is compressed with Deflate.

Closes #65.

commit.message:
Make reading compressed data more efficient.

This increases the chunk size for a significant speedup.

Improve code for retrieving compressed data of unknown length.

Do not assume we'll have the signature 0x08074b50 that is
sometimes used for the data description, because it is not
in the spec and is not always used.

Simplify complex code from
https://github.com/jgm/zip-archive/commit/4d66754458755e3279932608256d3a0d66830021

Closes #63.

Use `command -v` and THEN try `which`.

For bash `command` is better, as it's built in, but for busybox
`which` is needed.

Use 'command -v' rather than the non-standard 'which' in tests.

Closes #62.

Add needed import for Windows build.

Closes #61.

Fix problem with files with colon.

Closes #59.  This was due to overaggressive stripping
of windows drive.

Remove build-tools.

This was used to indicate that the 'unzip' executable was
needed for testing, but it was never intended to be used
this way and now the field is deprecated.

Supersedes #58.

The current test suite simply skips the test using the
unzip executable (with a warning) if 'unzip' is not in
the path.

See also #51 #41 #35 #23 #21.

Remove existing symlinks when extracting zip files with symlinks (#60)

Previously, writeEntry would raise an error if it tried to create a symlink
and a symlink already existed at that path.  This behavior was inconsistent
with its behavior for regular files, which it overwrote without comment.
This commit causes symlinks to be replaced by writeEntry instead of
an error being raised.

commit.message: Avoid MonadFail and revert base lower bound back to 4.5.

Remove binary < 0.6 CPP.

It's no longer needed because we don't support
binary < 0.6.

Also use manySig instead of many, to get better error
messages.

Better checking for unsafe paths.

This method allows things like `foo/bar/../../baz`.

See #55.

We should add some automated tests before closing this issue.
